Bike Share Case Study - 3 - Analysis

This analysis notebook will record the analysis of differences in bike share usage between members and casual riders.

Let’s look again at the numbers of rides by members and by casual riders.

bike_share %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = member_casual)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = member_casual), width = 0.5)

In 2021 there were about 3 million rides by members, and about 2.5 million rides by casual riders.

Analysis - Time distribution

Let’s look the time distributions of rides for the two types of users. We’ll look at ride counts per quarter and per month.

bike_share %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_quarter)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = member_casual)) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual) 

bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_month, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = ride_count)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 2, shape = 18)

There are more rides by casual riders than by members in the months June, July, and August. The numbers of rides by casual riders peak more sharply than the numbers of rides by members in the months May to October, and they fall off more in the colder months.

Let’s see how the percentages of rides by the two groups changed over time.

bike_share %>% 
  group_by(start_month, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = percent, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 100))

The percentages are nearly the same from May to September, but in other months there’s a significant difference in usage. In the colder months there are two or three times as many rides by members than by casual users.

Let’s look at rides per week.

bike_share %>% 
  group_by(start_week, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_week, y = ride_count)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual)) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual)

There appears to be more variability in the ride counts per week for casual riders. Let’s look at the weekly excess of rides for members (orange) and casual riders (blue).

bike_share %>% 
  group_by(start_week) %>%
  summarize(
    diff = sum(member_casual == "member") - sum(member_casual == "casual"),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_week, y = diff, fill = diff < 0)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle(label = "Member rides minus Casual rides")

Even though there are more rides by casual riders than by members in the summer months, the difference varies a lot from week to week. And a few weeks in the summer have more rides by members.

Let’s look at the percentage of rides by members on each day of the month as a check on data quality.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_mday) %>%
  summarize(percent_member = mean(member_casual == "member")) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_mday, y = percent_member)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = "member")) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

The percentage of rides by members is as expected, given the overall member/casual ride ratio of 6 to 5.

Now let’s look at rides by day of the week.

bike_share %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = member_casual)) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual)

Counts of rides by members show less variability by day of the week, and are generally lowest on Sunday. But rides by casual riders increase significantly on weekends.

Let’s look at ride percentage by user type and day of the week, across quarters. First we’ll look at rides by members.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  mutate(quarter = factor(start_quarter)) %>%
  group_by(quarter, start_wday) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(quarter) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday, y = percent, group = quarter)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = quarter)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = quarter), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ quarter) +
  ggtitle(label = "Quarterly member rides by day of the week")

There doesn’t seem to be a strong pattern for members. Sunday has the lowest percentage of rides in each quarter. Since quarters have different numbers of each day of the week, we should look at this monthly, and use only the first 28 days of the month so that each period has equal numbers of each day of the week.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "member" & start_mday < 29) %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_wday) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday, y = percent, group = start_month)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = start_month)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = start_month), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly member rides by day of the week (first 28 days)") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = substr(levels(bike_share$start_wday), 1, 1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

There still doesn’t appear to be a strong pattern. But during the high ride volume months of June through September the highest percentages of rides are usually on Wednesday or Thursday, and the lowest on Monday or Sunday.

Let’s look at the same plots for casual riders.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  mutate(quarter = factor(start_quarter)) %>%
  group_by(quarter, start_wday) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(quarter) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday, y = percent, group = quarter)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = quarter)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = quarter), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ quarter) +
  ggtitle(label = "Quarterly casual rides by day of the week")

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual" & start_mday < 29) %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_wday) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday, y = percent, group = start_month)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = start_month)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = start_month), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly casual rides by day of the week (first 28 days)") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = substr(levels(bike_share$start_wday), 1, 1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Casual riders have a strong pattern of increased rides on weekends, with Saturday having the highest percentage of rides in each period and Sunday usually having the second highest.

For each month, let’s compare the percentages of rides by the two groups of users on each day of the week.

 bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_wday) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday, y = percent, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month, nrow = 2) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = substr(levels(bike_share$start_wday), 1, 1)) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 100)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

In nearly all months the rides by members outnumber those by casual riders on Mondays, Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays. From April to October the rides by casual riders outnumber those by members on Saturdays and Sundays, and often on Fridays also.

Let’s look at plots to compare the two groups by the hour at which the rides begin.

bike_share %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = member_casual)) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual)

Let’s break it down by quarters.

bike_share %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = member_casual)) +
  facet_grid(member_casual ~ start_quarter)

The pattern for members has a small peak of rides around 8 a.m and a larger peak around 5 p.m. For casual riders there’s no morning peak, but there’s a peak around 5 p.m.

Let’s look at ride percentage by rider type and hour of the day, across quarters and months. First we’ll look at rides by members.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  mutate(quarter = factor(start_quarter)) %>%
  group_by(quarter, start_hour) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(quarter) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = quarter)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = quarter), size = 1) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ quarter) +
  ggtitle(label = "Quarterly member rides by hour of the day")

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_hour) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = start_month)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = start_month), size = 1) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly member rides by hour of the day") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

For members there’s a stable distribution for the percentage of rides by hour, having a small peak around 8 a.m. and a larger peak around 5 p.m.

Now we’ll look at the casual riders.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  mutate(quarter = factor(start_quarter)) %>%
  group_by(quarter, start_hour) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(quarter) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = quarter)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = quarter), size = 1) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ quarter) +
  ggtitle(label = "Quarterly causal rides by hour of the day")

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_hour) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = start_month)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = start_month), size = 1) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "mako", begin = 0.2, end = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly causal rides by hour of the day") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

For casual riders there’s also a stable distribution for percentage of rides by hour. It doesn’t have the peak around 8 a.m. The percentage rises fairly steadily from a low around 4 a.m. to a peak at 5 p.m. There’s also a higher percentage of rides in the late evening and early morning hours.

Now we’ll compare the two groups of users by percentages of rides per hour across all months.

 bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_hour, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month, start_hour) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month, nrow = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 100)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

In most months, casual rides outnumbered member rides in the early morning before 5 a.m. Then from 5 a.m. to 10 a.m. there were nearly always two to three times more rides by members than by casual riders. From March to October the percentages of rides by both groups were similar between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m., with casual riders taking more rides in the months May to September. In the warmer months there were more casual rides in the evenings.

Let’s look at percentage of rides by day of the week and by hour of the day within the member user group. We’ll look at each quarter.

 bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, start_hour, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  scale_color_discrete(drop = FALSE) +
  facet_grid(start_quarter ~ start_wday) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

Now we’ll look at the same for casual riders.

 bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, start_hour, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  scale_color_discrete(drop = FALSE) +
  facet_grid(start_quarter ~ start_wday) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

The plots for Saturday and Sunday look similar for both groups. Let’s plot both groups together to see where the differences lie.

 bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, start_hour, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  facet_grid(start_quarter ~ start_wday) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

This comparison shows that on Saturdays and Sundays, the distributions of rides by hour of the day are very similar for both user types. The significant differences in the bike use percentage by hour are limited to week days, in particular the peak of hourly percentage for member rides centered around 8 a.m., and less markedly the greater percentages of rides by casual users in the mid-afternoon and late evening.

Let’s compare the relative proportions of members and causal riders by hour and day of the week.

 bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_hour, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_hour, start_wday) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  facet_grid(start_quarter ~ start_wday) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 100)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

The curves for each user type and day of the week don’t change much in shape across quarters, especially in the high volume second and third quarters. But the relative heights of the curves come closer together in the second and third quarters when there are more casual riders. These plots show that rides by members nearly always outnumber those by casual riders, except on weekends in the second and third quarters, and in the late night and early morning hours of week days in those same quarters.

Analysis - Rideable_type

Let’s look ride counts by user type and bike type.

bike_share %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = rideable_type)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = rideable_type)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual)

Both groups use classic bikes more often than electric bikes. It appears that only casual riders use the docked bikes, but we’ll check that.

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "docked_bike") %>%
  group_by(member_casual) %>%
  count()

There was only one docked bike ride by a member.

Instead of ride counts, let’s look at the percentages of rides on each type of bike within the two groups.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(member_casual, rideable_type) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(member_casual) %>%
  mutate(
    percent = n / sum(n),
    label = paste(as.character(round(100 * percent, 1)), "%", sep = "")
  ) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = rideable_type, y = percent)) +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(fill = rideable_type)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  geom_text(mapping = aes(label = label), vjust = -0.5) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual)

Overall, both groups use electric bikes at the nearly the same rate. Among non-electric casual rides the ratio of classic to docked bikes is about 4 to 1.

Let’s see how these percentages change during the year. First we’ll look at rides by members.

bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  group_by(rideable_type, start_month) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = percent, group = rideable_type)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly member rides by bike type")

For members the relative percentages of rides on electric and classic bikes are stable until the last three months of the year, during which the percentage of rides on electric bikes increases and overtakes that of rides on classic bikes.

bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  group_by(rideable_type, start_month) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = percent, group = rideable_type)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly casual rides by bike type")

Rides by casual riders show more variability in choice of bike type in the first nine months of the year, but starting in October there’s the same shift from classic to electric bikes that was seen among rides by members. Also, from March to December there’s a gradual decrease in the percentage of rides on docked bikes. These changes in use of bike types could be due to a change in the availability of the different bike types, or in the cost of rides on different types of bikes. More information than what’s in the data would be needed to determine why these changes in use of bike types happened.

Let’s look at monthly percentages of electric bike rides by user type.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_month, rideable_type, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "electric_bike") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = percent, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 2, shape = 18) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly electric bike rides by user type")

Whatever caused the increase in the use of electric bikes at the end of the year, it appears to have had the same affect on both user groups. There doesn’t appear to be an any significant difference in preference for electric bikes between the two user groups.

Now let’s look at the same plot for classic bikes.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_month, rideable_type, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "classic_bike") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = percent, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 2, shape = 18) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly classic bike rides by user type")

Changes in classic bike use are also correlated between the two user groups. Since the groups use electric bikes at nearly the same percentages, the difference in use of classic bikes is mostly due to the use of docked bikes by casual riders.

Let’s compare the percentages of casual rides for classic and docked bikes only.

bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "casual" & rideable_type != "electric_bike") %>%
  group_by(start_month, rideable_type) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = percent, group = rideable_type)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type), size = 2, shape = 18) + 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Casual rider preference among rides not on electric bikes")

This plot shows that casual riders consistently use docked bikes about 15 to 25% of the time when they don’t use electric bikes. Whether this is due to user preference, bike availability, or something else can’t be determined without information beyond what’s in the data set.

Let’s see whether the day of the week affects the type of bike used by members.

bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "member" & start_mday < 29) %>%
  group_by(rideable_type, start_wday, start_month) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_wday, start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday, y = percent, group = rideable_type)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type), size = 2, shape = 18) + 
  scale_x_discrete(labels = substr(levels(bike_share$start_wday), 1, 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month, nrow = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly member rides by day of the week (first 28 days)")

Other than a slight increase in the percentage of classic bikes on weekends, along with a corresponding decrease in the percentage of electric bikes, the day of the week doesn’t have much affect on the choice of bike type for members.

Let’s look at the same plot for casual riders.

bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "casual" & start_mday < 29) %>%
  group_by(rideable_type, start_wday, start_month) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_wday, start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_wday, y = percent, group = rideable_type)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type), size = 2, shape = 18) + 
  scale_x_discrete(labels = substr(levels(bike_share$start_wday), 1, 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month, nrow = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly casual rides by day of the week (first 28 days)")

For casual riders there’s a more significant decrease in the percentages of rides with electric bikes on the weekends, and corresponding increases in rides on classic and docked bikes. This trend even extends into the last three months of the year, when electric bike use was greater than that of the other bike types.

Let’s use similar plots to check whether the hour of the day has an effect on bike type.

bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
  group_by(rideable_type, start_hour, start_month) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_hour, start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = rideable_type)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type), size = 1) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month, nrow = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly member rides by hour of the day")

For members the use of electric bikes increases in the late evening and early morning hours. The relative proportions of bike types are stable in the other parts of the day.

bike_share %>%
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  group_by(rideable_type, start_hour, start_month) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_hour, start_month) %>%
  mutate(percent = ride_count / sum(ride_count)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent, group = rideable_type)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = rideable_type), size = 1) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_month, nrow = 2) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "Monthly casual rides by hour of the day")

For casual riders, there’s more variability in choice of bike type throughout the day. If we focus on the high volume months May through September, we see a that electric bike use percentage is highest in the hours from 3 a.m. to 9 a.m., and levels out for the rest of the day. Classic bike use percentage dips during that period, and is fairly level the rest of the day except for a slight peak around 5 or 6 p.m. Docked bike use percentage is elevated in the period 10 a.m. to 3 p.m., and lowered in the period 4 a.m. to 7 a.m.

The patterns change in the last three months of the year, when hourly use percentages of electric and classic bikes are changing from month to month.

Let’s look at use for both hour of the day and day of the week, by quarters. We’ll look at each bike type separately.

 bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "electric_bike") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, start_hour, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  facet_grid(start_quarter ~ start_wday) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "Quarterly electric bike use by hour and day of the week")

 bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "classic_bike") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, start_hour, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  facet_grid(start_quarter ~ start_wday) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "Quarterly classic bike use by hour and day of the week")

 bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "docked_bike" & member_casual == "casual") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, start_hour, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(n = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, start_wday, member_casual) %>%
  mutate(percent = 100 * n / sum(n)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = percent)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  scale_color_discrete(drop = FALSE) +
  facet_grid(start_quarter ~ start_wday) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "Quarterly docked bike use by hour and day of the week")

The plots for electric and classic bikes resemble the plot we saw previously for overall bike use by week day and hour. The distributions for docked bikes on weekdays have peaks that are less narrow and sharp than those for electric and casual bikes on weekdays.

Analysis - Ride duration

Let’s look at density plots of ride duration for each user type. We’ll limit the x-axis to 90 minutes or less.

bike_share %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
                     x = ride_duration / 60, 
                     y = after_stat(density), 
                     group = member_casual,
                     color = member_casual
                   )
  ) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 1, size = 1) +
  xlab("Minutes") +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 90), ylim = c(0, 0.1))

It’s clear that there’s a difference in ride duration between the two groups.

Let’s see how the type of bike affects the median and mean ride duration for each group.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(rideable_type, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(
    median_duration_min = round(median(ride_duration) / 60, 1),
    mean_duration_min = round(mean(ride_duration) / 60, 1),
    count = n(),
    .groups = "keep"
  )
NA

Compared to members, casual riders have median ride times that are about 4 minutes longer on electric bikes and about 6 minutes longer on classic bikes.

Let’s plot the distributions of each type of user by bike type. Since there was only one ride by a member on a docked bike, we’ll remove it from the data for this analysis. We’ll limit the x-axis to 45 minutes or less to see more detail.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" | member_casual != "member") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
                     x = ride_duration / 60, 
                     y = after_stat(density), 
                     group = member_casual,
                     color = member_casual
                   )
  ) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 1, size = 1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:22 * 2) +
  xlab("Minutes") +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 45), ylim = c(0, 0.1)) +
  facet_wrap(~ rideable_type, nrow = 3)

The docked bikes have a very different distribution compared to electric and classic bikes. And we see the difference in ride times for members and casual rides on electric and classic bikes.

Let’s rearrange these plots to put all the bike types together for each type of user.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" | member_casual != "member") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
                     x = ride_duration / 60, 
                     y = after_stat(density),

                     color = rideable_type

  ) +

For members, the ride time distributions are nearly the same for electric and classic bikes. Let’s see whether that holds across quarters. First we’ll look at rides by members.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" & member_casual == "member") %>%

                     x = ride_duration / 60,

  facet_wrap(~ start_quarter, nrow = 1) +
  ggtitle(label = "Members by Quarter")

The distributions for electric and classic bikes agree well in each quarter, particularly in the high volume second and third quarters. The peaks are higher in the colder months, indicating a decrease in ride times.

Now let’s look as the plots for casual riders.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
                     x = ride_duration / 60, 
                     y = after_stat(density), 
                     group = rideable_type,

The distributions for electric and classic bikes don’t agree as well as they did for rides by members, but they’re very similar. The distributions for all three bike types look stable across quarters, with expected decreases in ride duration in the colder months.

But because of the distinction for electric and classic bikes, we’ll add a column to the data set to classify each day as a weekday or a weekend. This will simplify the analysis for those bike types.

bike_share <- bike_share %>%
  mutate(wkend = factor(
                   ifelse(start_wday %in% c("Sat", "Sun"), "Weekend", "Weekday")
                 )
  )

Let’s look at density plots of ride duration for all bike types on weekdays and weekends.

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" | member_casual != "member") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
                     x = ride_duration / 60, 
                     y = after_stat(density), 
                     group = rideable_type,
                     color = rideable_type
                   ) 
  ) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 1, size = 1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:9 * 5) +
  xlab("Minutes") +
  scale_color_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 45), ylim = c(0, 0.08)) +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  ggtitle(label = "All Bike Types, Weekdays and Weekends")

In these plots we see that rides by casual riders tend to be longer on weekdays and weekends than rides by members. We also see that bike type has a greater impact on the ride time distribution for casual riders than it does for members.

Let’s look at the medians, first quartiles, third quartiles, and interquartile ranges of ride durations for each user group and bike type. We’ll also treat weekdays and weekends separately, and we’ll get values for each quarter of the year.

First we’ll look at electric bikes. We’ll make boxplots of ride duration. The line inside each box represents the median of ride duration, while the bottoms and tops of each box represent the 25th and 75th percentiles of ride duration, respectively.

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "electric_bike") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_quarter, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_quarter, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +
  ylab("Minutes") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 35)) +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Duration Boxplots, Electric Bikes")

We see that for electric bikes the median ride times are slightly decreased in the first and fourth quarters, probably due to colder weather. We also see that rides by casual riders are generally longer than rides by members.

Rides by casual riders also have a larger interquartile range (IQR), which is the difference between the 75th percentile and the 25th percentile of ride duration, as seen by the greater heights of the boxes for casual riders.

On both weekdays and weekends, and in all quarters of the year, rides by casual riders have higher medians, 25th percentiles, and 75th percentiles than do the rides by members.

Also, the distributions are fairly stable across the year except for expected decreases in ride duration in the colder months.

Let’s look at the same for classic bikes.

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "classic_bike") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_quarter, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_quarter, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +
  ylab("Minutes") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 35)) +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Duration Boxplots, Classic Bikes")

The plots for classic bikes show the same contrasts between members and casual riders that were seen in the plots for electric bikes. But for the classic bikes there’s a significant upward shift in median and IQR for the casual riders.

Now let’s look at box plots for docked bikes. We’ll need to use a different scale for the y-axis since these rides last longer.

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "docked_bike" & member_casual == "casual") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_quarter, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_quarter, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA,

  ggtitle(label = "Ride Duration Boxplots, Docked Bikes")

The stats for these rides also look stable over the quarters of the year.

Let’s summarize the data on median ride duration with a bar plot.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" | member_casual != "member") %>%
  group_by(wkend, rideable_type, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(median = median(ride_duration) / 60 , .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = wkend, y = median)) +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(fill = rideable_type), position = "dodge") +
  ylab("Minutes") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Median Ride Duration")

And let’s also summarize the stats in a box plot.

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" | member_casual != "member") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = wkend, y = ride_duration / 60)) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(fill = rideable_type), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +
  ylab("Minutes") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "plasma", end = 0.8, drop = FALSE) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 60)) +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Duration Boxplots")

While these differences in medians or IQR may seem small, they represent significant differences in behavior among the two user groups. For example, the cumulative distribution function below shows, for x number of minutes on the x-axis, the percentage of rides that last x minutes or less. For rides on classic bikes on weekends, about 65% of rides by members are 15 minutes or less, but only 40% of rides by casual riders are 15 minutes or less.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(rideable_type == "classic_bike" & wkend == "Weekend") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = ride_duration / 60,  group = member_casual)) +
  stat_ecdf(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  geom_segment(
    mapping = aes(x = 0, y = 0.65, xend = 15, yend = 0.65), 
    linetype = 2
  ) +
  geom_segment(
    mapping = aes(x = 0, y = 0.40, xend = 15, yend = 0.40), 
    linetype = 2
  ) +
  geom_segment(
    mapping = aes(x = 15, y = 0, xend = 15, yend = 0.65), 
    linetype  = 2
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:12 * 5) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = 0:10 / 10, labels = scales::percent) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 60)) +
  xlab("Minutes") +
  ylab("Percentage of rides with duration less than x minutes") +
  ggtitle("Classic Bikes on Weekends")

Let’s plot cumulative distribution functions for each bike type and for weekdays and weekends.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" | member_casual != "member") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = ride_duration / 60,  group = member_casual)) +
  stat_ecdf(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +

  scale_y_continuous(breaks = 0:10 / 10, labels = scales::percent) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 60)) +
  xlab("Minutes") +
  ylab("Percentage of rides with duration less than x minutes") +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ rideable_type) +
  ggtitle("Ride Duration Cumulative Distribution Functions")

Let’s also put all bike types in one plot for each user group, and for weekdays and weekends.

bike_share %>% 
  filter(rideable_type != "docked_bike" | member_casual != "member") %>%

And we’ll plot the overall cumulative distributions for weekdays and for weekends.

                     x = ride_duration / 60,  
                     group = interaction(member_casual, wkend)
                   )
  ) +
  stat_ecdf(mapping = aes(color = member_casual, linetype = wkend), size = 1) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 0:6 * 10) +

  facet_wrap(~ rideable_type, nrow = 2) +
  ggtitle("Ride Duration Cumulative Distribution Functions")

Now let’s look at how ride durations vary by hour of the day. We’ll start by looking at density plots for each hour. We’ll limit the x-axis to 45 minutes or less.

bike_share %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
                     x = ride_duration / 60, 
                     y = after_stat(density), 
                     group = member_casual,
                     color = member_casual
                   )
  ) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 1, size = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_hour) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 45))

For most hours of the day the ride duration distributions are similar to the overall distributions for members and casual riders. But during the hours 6 to 8 a.m. the distributions for the two user groups are very close. Presumably this represents users going to work in the morning, so we wouldn’t expect longer rides at this period in the day. Also, we’ve already seen that the numbers of rides by casual riders are low at that time of day, at least on weekdays.

Let’s look at boxplots of ride duration for each hour, divided into weekdays and weekends.

bike_share %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_hour, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +
  ylab("Minutes") +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 40)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Duration Boxplots")

For members there isn’t a lot of variation in ride duration during the course of the day on weekdays or weekends. For casual riders, median ride duration and IQR are lowest around 4 to 7 a.m. and peak around 10 a.m. to 3 p.m.

Let’s check whether bike type has an affect on these patterns.

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "electric_bike") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_hour, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "classic_bike") %>%

    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0,

  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 40)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Duration Boxplots, Classic Bikes")

bike_share %>%
  filter(rideable_type == "docked_bike" & member_casual == "casual") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_hour, fill = member_casual),

  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 80)) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Duration Boxplots, Docked Bikes")

The general pattern stays the same for electric and classic bikes. There’s more variation in rides duration during the day for docked bikes, but they represent only about 12% of rides by casual riders.

Let’s check whether there’s an seasonal variation in ride duration by hour of the day. We’ll look at rides by quarter on weekdays and on weekends.

bike_share %>%
  filter(wkend == "Weekday") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +
  geom_boxplot(

bike_share %>%

  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = ride_duration / 60) ) +

    mapping = aes(group = start_hour, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge",

    coef = 0,

  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 40)) +

The patterns don’t change much based on the time of the year.

Let’s plot the median ride durations for each rider group by hour of the day.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(start_hour, member_casual, wkend) %>%
  summarize(median = median(ride_duration) / 60, .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = median, group = member_casual)) +
  geom_line(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 1) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = member_casual), size = 2, shape = 18) +
  ylab("Minutes") +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 25)) +
  facet_wrap(~ wkend) +
  ggtitle(label = "Median Ride Duration, by Hour of the Day")

The median ride duration for casual riders has a lot of variation, depending on the time of day, and on whether it’s a weekday or weekend. For members, the median ride duration is fairly constant through the hours of the day, and only slightly elevated on weekends.

Analysis - Location Data

We’ll start by adding two columns, lat and lng, to the data set, using ride start latitude and longitude, rounded to two decimal places.

bike_share <- bike_share %>%
  mutate(
    lat = round(start_lat, 2), 
    lng = round(start_lng, 2)
  )

Now we’ll look at the geographic distributions of ride start locations for members and for casual riders.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng, member_casual) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = ride_count), size = 2.5) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  bike_coord +
  facet_wrap(~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Counts")

There isn’t much difference in where the rides begin, keeping in mind that the overall ratio of rides by members to rides by casual riders is about 6 to 5.

Let’s see whether there are any quarters in which there’s a difference in ride locations. We’ll look at both weekdays and weekends.

bike_share %>%
  filter(start_quarter == 1) %>%
  group_by(lat, lng, member_casual, wkend) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = ride_count), size = 1.3) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  bike_coord +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Counts, First Quarter")

bike_share %>%
  filter(start_quarter == 2) %>%
  group_by(lat, lng, member_casual, wkend) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = ride_count), size = 1.3) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  bike_coord +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Counts, Second Quarter")

bike_share %>%
  filter(start_quarter == 3) %>%
  group_by(lat, lng, member_casual, wkend) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = ride_count), size = 1.3) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  bike_coord +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Counts, Third Quarter")

bike_share %>%
  filter(start_quarter == 4) %>%
  group_by(lat, lng, member_casual, wkend) %>%
  summarize(ride_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = ride_count), size = 1.3) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() +
  bike_coord +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  ggtitle(label = "Ride Counts, Fourth Quarter")

Given that we know there were low numbers of rides by casual users in the first and fourth quarters, and given that casual riders are most active on weekends, there’s nothing unusual in these plots.

Another way to compare members and casual riders is to look at the percentages of rides by each group at each location. We’ll use a gradient of color from orange (0%) to blue (100%) to represent the percentage of rides at that were by casual riders.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng) %>%
  summarize(
    pct_casual  = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"),
    count = n(),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = pct_casual), size = 2.5) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#F8766D", high = "#00BFC4", limits = c(0, 100)) +
  bike_coord +
  ggtitle(label = "Percentage of Casual Riders")

The blue locations have high percentages of rides by casual riders, and the orange locations have low percentages of rides by casual riders.

There are many locations in the south and west of the city that have high percentages of casual riders. But we have to consider that these locations may not have high numbers of rides. Let’s plot only locations that average no more than two rides per day.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng) %>%
  summarize(
    pct_casual  = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"),
    count = n(),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>% 
  filter(count <= 365 * 2) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = pct_casual), size = 2.5) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#F8766D", high = "#00BFC4", limits = c(0, 100)) +
  bike_coord +
  ggtitle(label = "Percentage of Casual Riders (average <= 2 rides per day)")

These locations are the majority, but they represent a small proportion of the total rides. There are 383 points on this plot, and even if each point had an average of two rides per day, they would represent less than 280,000 of the over 5.5 million total rides.

Let’s look at the locations which average more than ten rides a day.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng) %>%
  summarize(
    pct_casual  = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"),
    count = n(),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>% 
  filter(count > 365 * 10) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = pct_casual), size = 2.5) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#F8766D", high = "#00BFC4", limits = c(0, 100)) +
  bike_coord +
  ggtitle(label = "Percentage of Casual Riders (average > 10 rides per day)")

There are some locations along the lake shore where casual riders predominate. Let’s look at this plot by quarter, and make separate plots for weekdays and weekends.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng) %>%
  mutate(count = n()) %>%
  filter(count > 365 * 10) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(wkend == "Weekday") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, lat, lng) %>%
  summarize(
    pct_casual  = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = pct_casual), size = 1.5) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#F8766D", high = "#00BFC4", limits = c(0, 100)) +
  bike_coord +
  ggtitle(
    label = "Percentage of Casual Riders, Weekdays (avg > 10 rides per day)"
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_quarter, nrow = 1)

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng) %>%
  mutate(count = n()) %>%
  filter(count > 365 * 10) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(wkend == "Weekend") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter, lat, lng) %>%
  summarize(
    pct_casual  = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = pct_casual), size = 1.5) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#F8766D", high = "#00BFC4", limits = c(0, 100)) +
  bike_coord +
  ggtitle(
    label = "Percentage of Casual Riders, Weekends (avg > 10 rides per day)"
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_quarter, nrow = 1)

Members dominate in the first and fourth quarters, as expected. But in all quarters there are locations along the lake shore where casual riders dominate, especially on weekends.

Another way to look for locations with unusual percentages of casual riders is calculate how much the percentage of casual rides at each location differs from the quarterly average for all locations. We’ll do this for each quarter, for weekdays and weekends. We’ll also zoom in.

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng) %>%
  mutate(count = n()) %>%
  filter(count > 365 * 10) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(wkend == "Weekday") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter) %>%
  mutate(pct_casual_overall = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"))  %>% 
  group_by(start_quarter, pct_casual_overall, lat, lng) %>%
  summarize(
    pct_casual  = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"),
    count = n(),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(pct_diff = pct_casual - pct_casual_overall) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = pct_diff), size = 2.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-87.7, -87.6)) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#F8766D", high = "#00BFC4", limits = c(-35, 35)) +
  coord_quickmap(xlim = c(-87.75, -87.55), ylim = c(41.75, 42.07)) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_quarter, nrow = 1) +
  ggtitle(
    label = "Casual Riders, Weekdays, Percent Difference from Quarterly Average"
  )

bike_share %>%
  group_by(lat, lng) %>%
  mutate(count = n()) %>%
  filter(count > 365 * 10) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(wkend == "Weekend") %>%
  group_by(start_quarter) %>%
  mutate(pct_casual_overall = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"))  %>% 
  group_by(start_quarter, pct_casual_overall, lat, lng) %>%
  summarize(
    pct_casual  = 100 * mean(member_casual == "casual"),
    count = n(),
    .groups = "keep"
  ) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(pct_diff = pct_casual - pct_casual_overall) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = lng, y = lat)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = pct_diff), size = 2.5) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(-87.7, -87.6)) +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "#F8766D", high = "#00BFC4", limits = c(-35, 35)) +
  coord_quickmap(xlim = c(-87.75, -87.55), ylim = c(41.75, 42.07)) +
  facet_wrap(~ start_quarter, nrow = 1) +
  ggtitle(
    label = "Casual Riders, Weekends, Percent Difference from Quarterly Average"
  )

In these plots the blue to orange scale indicates the extent to which the percentage of casual riders at the location is above or below the percentage of total casual riders for that quarter.

What stands out in these plots is that casual riders dominate in areas near the lake shore in the city center, in all quarters and on both weekdays and weekends, and members consistently dominate in areas of the city center just west of the lake shore.

Analysis - Ride Displacement

Let’s see whether there are any significant differences in ride displacement between members and casual riders. We’ll look at boxplots for weekdays and weekends.

bike_share %>%
  filter(!is.na(ride_displacement)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = member_casual, y = ride_displacement) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = member_casual, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +
  facet_wrap(~ wkend) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 0.05))

The difference between the groups is slight. Let’s look at monthly and hourly boxplots.

bike_share %>%
  filter(!is.na(ride_displacement)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_month, y = ride_displacement) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_month, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = substr(levels(bike_share$start_month), 1, 1)) +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 0.05)) 

bike_share %>%
  filter(!is.na(ride_displacement)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = start_hour, y = ride_displacement) ) +
  geom_boxplot(
    mapping = aes(group = start_hour, fill = member_casual), 
    position = "dodge", 
    outlier.shape = NA, 
    coef = 0, 
  ) +
  facet_grid(wkend ~ member_casual) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 0.05))

There’s not a notable difference in ride displacement between the two groups.
